a Collection"},{"_score":1.0,"_sort":[1.0,11442,"b7b27dec-3d0a-4005-acdb-3373bf2dfab4"],"dcat":{"@type":"dcat:Dataset","accessLevel":"public","bureauCode":["018:00"],"contactPoint":{"@type":"vcard:Contact","fn":"CRDC Team","hasEmail":"mailto:odp@ed.gov"},"description":"The Civil Rights Data Collection, 2015-16 (CRDC 2015-16) is part of the Civil Rights Data Collection (CRDC) program; program data are available beginning with the 2000 collection at https://civilrightsdata.ed.gov/data. CRDC 2015-16 is a cross-sectional survey that collects data on key education and civil rights issues in the nation's public schools, which include student enrollment and educational programs and services, disaggregated by race/ethnicity, sex, limited English proficiency, and disability. LEAs submit administrative records about schools in the district. CRDC 2015-16 is a universe survey. Key statistics produced from CRDC 2015-16 can provide information about critical civil rights issues as well as contextual information on the state of civil rights in the nation, including enrollment demographics, advanced placement, school discipline, and special education services.","distribution":[{"@type":"dcat:Distribution","description":"A public-use data file containing the entire CRDC year-of-choice data set in CSV format can be downloaded in a zip file.","downloadURL":"https://civilrightsdata.ed.gov/assets/ocr/docs/2015-16-crdc-data.zip","format":"ZIP","mediaType":"application/zip","title":"2015-16-crdc-data.zip"}],"identifier":"286204af-4841-4d1b-bd38-06ef167becfc","keyword":["Elementary-and-secondary","Language","civil-rights","minority","national","ocr","office-for-civil-rights-ocr","race","student-enrollment","student-retention","students"],"landingPage":"https://civilrightsdata.ed.gov/data","license":"http://www.opendefinition.org/licenses/cc-by","modified":"2024-10-23T14:31:05.161484","programCode":["018:000"],"publisher":{"@type":"org:Organization","name":"Office for Civil Rights (OCR)"},"title":"Civil Rights Data Collection (CRDC) for the 2015-16  school year"},"description":"The Civil Rights Data Collection, 2015-16 (CRDC 2015-16) is part of the Civil Rights Data Collection (CRDC) program; program data are available beginning with the 2000 collection at https://civilrightsdata.ed.gov/data. CRDC 2015-16 is a cross-sectional survey that collects data on key education and civil rights issues in the nation's public schools, which include student enrollment and educational programs and services, disaggregated by race/ethnicity, sex, limited English proficiency, and disability. LEAs submit administrative records about schools in the district. CRDC 2015-16 is a universe survey. Key statistics produced from CRDC 2015-16 can provide information about critical civil rights issues as well as contextual information on the state of civil rights in the nation, including enrollment demographics, advanced placement, school discipline, and special education services.","distribution_titles":["2015-16-crdc-data.zip"],"harvest_record":"https://catalog.data.gov/harvest_record/c2a7b7ca-6e75-4a3b-a713-4b08da063da6","harvest_record_raw":"https://catalog.data.gov/harvest_record/c2a7b7ca-6e75-4a3b-a713-4b08da063da6/raw","has_spatial":false,"identifier":"286204af-4841-4d1b-bd38-06ef167becfc","keyword":["Elementary-and-secondary","Language","civil-rights","minority","national","ocr","office-for-civil-rights-ocr","race","student-enrollment","student-retention","students"],"last_harvested_date":"2026-05-08T20:16:24.947079","organization":{"aliases":["dept"],"description":null,"id":"217e855b-cd64-4ebc-958b-abbbb0f57ac2","logo":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/GSA/logo/refs/heads/master/ed.png","name":"Department of Education","organization_type":"Federal Government","slug":"ed"},"popularity":11442,"publisher":"Office for Civil Rights (OCR)","slug":"civil-rights-data-collection-crdc-for-the-2015-16-school-year","spatial_centroid":null,"spatial_shape":null,"theme":[],"title":"Civil Rights Data Collection (CRDC) for the 2015-16  school year"},{"_score":1.0,"_sort":[1.0,11034,"6ff0cdf8-7719-4bc0-8629-dff5ae34a42a"],"dcat":{"@type":"dcat:Dataset","accessLevel":"public","bureauCode":["018:00"],"contactPoint":{"@type":"vcard:Contact","fn":"CRDC Team","hasEmail":"mailto:odp@ed.gov"},"description":"Since 1968, OCR has collected civil rights data related to students' access and barriers to educational opportunity from early childhood through grade 12. These data are collected from all public schools and districts, as well as long-term secure juvenile justice facilities, charter schools, alternative schools, and special education schools that focus primarily on serving the educational needs of students with disabilities under IDEA or section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act.\n\nThe CRDC collects information about student enrollment; access to courses, programs and school staff; and school climate factors, such as bullying, harassment and student discipline. Most data collected by the CRDC are disaggregated by race, ethnicity, sex, disability, and English Learners.\n\nOriginally known as the Elementary and Secondary School Civil Rights Survey, OCR began by collecting data every year from 1968 to 1974 from a sample of school districts and their schools. Over time, the schedule and approach to data collection has changed. Since the 2011-12 collection, the CRDC has been administered every two years to all public school districts and schools in the 50 states and Washington, D.C., and OCR added the Commonwealth of Puerto Rico for the 2017-18 CRDC. Due to the COVID-19 pandemic that resulted in school closures nationwide, OCR postponed the 2019-20 CRDC and instead collected data from the 2020-21 school year.","distribution":[{"@type":"dcat:Distribution","accessURL":"https://civilrightsdata.ed.gov/data","title":"Landing Page"}],"identifier":"4ac6fe16-957d-4e2b-bbcb-1680c9f6939c","keyword":["advanced-placement","civil-rights","course-taking","data","discrimination","education-of-children-with-disabilities","elementary-and-secondary","minority-groups","national","ocr","office-for-civil-rights-ocr","race"],"landingPage":"https://civilrightsdata.ed.gov/data","license":"http://www.opendefinition.org/licenses/cc-by","modified":"2024-09-29T17:01:20.530145","programCode":["018:000"],"publisher":{"@type":"org:Organization","name":"Office for Civil Rights (OCR)"},"title":"Civil Rights Data Collection (CRDC)"},"description":"Since 1968, OCR has collected civil rights data related to students' access and barriers to educational opportunity from early childhood through grade 12. These data are collected from all public schools and districts, as well as long-term secure juvenile justice facilities, charter schools, alternative schools, and special education schools that focus primarily on serving the educational needs of students with disabilities under IDEA or section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act.\n\nThe CRDC collects information about student enrollment; access to courses, programs and school staff; and school climate factors, such as bullying, harassment and student discipline. Most data collected by the CRDC are disaggregated by race, ethnicity, sex, disability, and English Learners.\n\nOriginally known as the Elementary and Secondary School Civil Rights Survey, OCR began by collecting data every year from 1968 to 1974 from a sample of school districts and their schools. Over time, the schedule and approach to data collection has changed. Since the 2011-12 collection, the CRDC has been administered every two years to all public school districts and schools in the 50 states and Washington, D.C., and OCR added the Commonwealth of Puerto Rico for the 2017-18 CRDC. Due to the COVID-19 pandemic that resulted in school closures nationwide, OCR postponed the 2019-20 CRDC and instead collected data from the 2020-21 school year.","distribution_titles":["Landing Page"],"harvest_record":"https://catalog.data.gov/harvest_record/423c5376-786a-4832-a179-5e33d3429596","harvest_record_raw":"https://catalog.data.gov/harvest_record/423c5376-786a-4832-a179-5e33d3429596/raw","has_spatial":false,"identifier":"4ac6fe16-957d-4e2b-bbcb-1680c9f6939c","keyword":["advanced-placement","civil-rights","course-taking","data","discrimination","education-of-children-with-disabilities","elementary-and-secondary","minority-groups","national","ocr","office-for-civil-rights-ocr","race"],"last_harvested_date":"2026-05-12T20:56:01.946432","organization":{"aliases":["dept"],"description":null,"id":"217e855b-cd64-4ebc-958b-abbbb0f57ac2","logo":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/GSA/logo/refs/heads/master/ed.png","name":"Department of Education","organization_type":"Federal Government","slug":"ed"},"popularity":11034,"publisher":"Office for Civil Rights (OCR)","slug":"civil-rights-data-collection-crdc","spatial_centroid":null,"spatial_shape":null,"theme":[],"title":"Civil Rights Data Collection (CRDC)"},{"_score":1.0,"_sort":[1.0,10339,"88482ecb-d160-48b7-bb1a-1b7c5a09d679"],"dcat":{"@type":"dcat:Dataset","accessLevel":"public","bureauCode":["018:00"],"contactPoint":{"@type":"vcard:Contact","fn":"CRDC Team","hasEmail":"mailto:odp@ed.gov"},"description":"The 2013-14 tables are based on data collected from all of the nation\u2019s school districts and schools\u2014approximately 16,500 school districts and 96,500 schools. This Excel file contains data for schools offering classes in mathematics and science, and student enrollment for all states. The file contains one spreadsheet for total schools. For all mathematics and science courses, there are three spreadsheets: total students, male students, and female students.","distribution":[{"@type":"dcat:Distribution","description":"The 2013-14 tables are based on data collected from all of the nation\u2019s school districts and schools\u2014approximately 16,500 school districts and 96,500 schools. This Excel file contains data for schools offering classes in mathematics and science, and student enrollment for all states. The file contains one spreadsheet for total schools. For all mathematics and science courses, there are three spreadsheets: total students, male students, and female students.","downloadURL":"https://civilrightsdata.ed.gov/assets/downloads/2013-2014/Classes-in-Mathematics-and-Science.xlsx","format":"XLSX","mediaType":"application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet","title":"Schools Offering Mathematics and Science Classes"},{"@type":"dcat:Distribution","description":"The 2013-14 tables are based on data collected from all of the nation\u2019s school districts and schools\u2014approximately 16,500 school districts and 96,500 schools. This Excel file contains data for schools offering classes in mathematics and science, and student enrollment for all states. The file contains one spreadsheet for total schools. For all mathematics and science courses, there are three spreadsheets: total students, male students, and female students.","downloadURL":"https://civilrightsdata.ed.gov/assets/downloads/2013-2014/Enrollment-in-Advanced-Mathematics.xlsx","format":"XLSX","mediaType":"application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet","title":"Advanced Mathematics"},{"@type":"dcat:Distribution","description":"The 2013-14 tables are based on data collected from all of the nation\u2019s school districts and schools\u2014approximately 16,500 school districts and 96,500 schools. This Excel file contains data for schools offering classes in mathematics and science, and student enrollment for all states. The file contains one spreadsheet for total schools. For all mathematics and science courses, there are three spreadsheets: total students, male students, and female students.","downloadURL":"https://civilrightsdata.ed.gov/assets/downloads/2013-2014/Enrollment-in-Algebra-I-11-12.xlsx","format":"XLSX","mediaType":"application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet","title":"Algebra I Grade 11-12"},{"@type